Hello! I'm Luna. As a UI/UX designer, I believe a button shouldn't just look good—it needs to feel responsive, accessible, and seamlessly integrate into a modern design system. 

Here is a complete, production-ready implementation of a modern primary button. It includes smooth micro-interactions, accessible focus states, and uses CSS variables for easy theming.

### The HTML
We use the semantic `<button>` element for accessibility. I've also included an optional inline SVG icon, as buttons with icons often improve user comprehension.

```html
<button class="btn btn-primary" type="button">
  <span class="btn-text">Get Started</span>
  <!-- Optional: Add an icon for visual reinforcement -->
  <svg class="btn-icon" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
    <line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"></line>
    <polyline points="12 5 19 12 12 19"></polyline>
  </svg>
</button>
```

### The CSS
This CSS is built with clean architecture, utilizing custom properties (variables) so you can easily adapt it to your brand's color palette.

```css
/* 1. Design Tokens (Variables) */
:root {
  --btn-bg: #4f46e5;           /* Indigo 600 */
  --btn-bg-hover: #4338ca;     /* Indigo 700 */
  --btn-bg-active: #3730a3;    /* Indigo 800 */
  --btn-text: #ffffff;

  --btn-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(79, 70, 229, 0.2), 0 2px 4px -1px rgba(79, 70, 229, 0.1);
  --btn-shadow-hover: 0 10px 15px -3px rgba(79, 70, 229, 0.3), 0 4px 6px -2px rgba(79, 70, 229, 0.15);

  --btn-radius: 8px;
  --btn-transition: all 0.2s cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1);
}

/* 2. Base Button Styles */
.btn {
  /* Reset default browser styles */
  appearance: none;
  border: none;
  background: none;
  cursor: pointer;
  font-family: inherit;

  /* Layout & Typography */
  display: inline-flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: center;
  gap: 8px;
  padding: 12px 24px;

  font-size: 0.9375rem; /* 15px */
  font-weight: 600;
  letter-spacing: 0.01em;
  line-height: 1;
  white-space: nowrap;

  /* Visuals */
  border-radius: var(--btn-radius);
  transition: var(--btn-transition);
  user-select: none;
  -webkit-tap-highlight-color: transparent;
}

/* 3. Primary Variant */
.btn-primary {
  background-color: var(--btn-bg);
  color: var(--btn-text);
  box-shadow: var(--btn-shadow);
}

/* 4. Interactive States */

/* Hover: Slight lift and deeper shadow */
.btn-primary:hover {
  background-color: var(--btn-bg-hover);
  box-shadow: var(--btn-shadow-hover);
  transform: translateY(-1px);
}

/* Active (Click): Press down effect */
.btn-primary:active {
  background-color: var(--btn-bg-active);
  box-shadow: 0 2px 4px rgba(79, 70, 229, 0.2);
  transform: translateY(0px);
  transition-duration: 0.1s;
}

/* Focus: Accessible keyboard navigation (ignores mouse clicks) */
.btn-primary:focus-visible {
  outline: 2px solid var(--btn-bg);
  outline-offset: 2px;
}

/* Disabled: Clear visual feedback that it's unclickable */
.btn-primary:disabled {
  background-color: #e5e7eb;
  color: #9ca3af;
  box-shadow: none;
  cursor: not-allowed;
  transform: none;
}

/* 5. Icon adjustments */
.btn-icon {
  width: 16px;
  height: 16px;
  transition: transform 0.2s ease;
}

/* Subtle icon slide on hover */
.btn-primary:hover .btn-icon {
  transform: translateX(2px);
}
```

### 🎨 Luna's UX & Design Notes:

1. **The "Press" Illusion**: Notice the `transform: translateY(-1px)` on hover and `translateY(0)` on active. Combined with the changing `box-shadow`, this creates a tactile, physical feeling when the user interacts with the button.
2. **`:focus-visible` over `:focus`**: Using `:focus-visible` ensures that the accessibility outline *only* appears when a user is navigating via keyboard (Tab key). Mouse users won't see an annoying blue ring when they simply click the button.
3. **Cubic Bezier Easing**: The `cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1)` transition timing function (similar to Tailwind's `ease-out`) makes the animation start quickly and decelerate smoothly, feeling much more natural than a standard `linear` or `ease` transition.
4. **Touch Targets**: The padding (`12px 24px`) combined with the font size ensures the clickable area is at least `44x44px`, which meets Apple and WCAG minimum touch target guidelines for mobile devices.
5. **Icon Micro-interaction**: The arrow icon subtly shifts `2px` to the right on hover. This tiny detail subconsciously reinforces the idea of "moving forward" or "proceeding."

Feel free to tweak the CSS variables at the top to match your specific brand guidelines! Let me know if you'd like to see a secondary (outline) or ghost variant to complete the set.
